    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The strongest philosophical argument is that government regulation inherently creates a \"chilling effect,\" where the fear of punishment silences dissent before it even happens. This violates the core principle that free speech must be absolute to function as a true check on power, as any state authority has the capacity to censor based on political bias rather than objective harm. Furthermore, the concept of a \"public square\" relies on the idea that all voices are equal; when the government acts as the gatekeeper, it inevitably privileges its own agenda over the diverse opinions of the citizenry. Therefore, any regulatory framework that restricts content is fundamentally an act of authoritarianism that undermines the very foundation of a free society.",
